{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Generated function signature matches the expected interface from the natural-language spec.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Failure boundary is the model’s code-generation decision, not just local parsing. A stubbed model can always emit a perfect signature and hide real mismatches. No real OS/subprocess requirement is stated, and this behavior is about one model output check (not a multi-step agent pipeline), so Agentic is the minimum. Rejected higher level (Workflow): behavior text checks a single generated signature, not multiple agentic decisions in sequence.","test_description":"Run the service against real LLM generation prompts with explicit interface constraints, compile/inspect the produced function signature, and assert parameter names/types/return type match expected interface.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Orchestration runs attempts in order and exits immediately on first pass.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration/state-handoff logic across generator, test runner, and attempt bookkeeping modules. A one-function unit test is insufficient for realistic handoff/order bugs. It does not require real OS/network/subprocess, and correctness does not depend on model output quality if deterministic stubs are used. Rejected higher levels: no behavior text requiring real infra or real model judgment.","test_description":"Wire orchestrator with deterministic stub generator and stub test executor (fail then pass), assert call order, assert no further attempt after first pass, and verify attempt metadata.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For problems where one-shot usually fails